If control was done in the field, select the different methods that were used:
•	Biocontrol - the use of natural enemies
•	Biopesticide - the use of a biological pesticide (BT, neem and others)
•	Cultural - any cultural practices such as planting dates, planting with an associated crop or plant
•	Chemical pesticide - the use of a synthetic chemical pesticide (not recommended)
•	Egg-squashing - smashing the egg clusters on the top and bottom of the leaves with your thumb
•	Hand-picking - of larvae from the leaves
•	Traditional control - the use of sand, ash, soil, oils, soaps, fish soup and others
•	Plowing - deep tillage to destroy the pupae in the soil

data.en: Roughly how much previous FAW damage is on the lower, older leaves? If the damaged leaves have grown out of the whorl (funnel) and there are fresh, undamaged leaves, then the FAW caterpillar is no longer feeding in the whorl. This is old damage. You may also see scratches on the older parts of the leaves. This is damage from young larvae that may have moved into the whorl, been killed, or moved to another plant.

data.en: Euborellia annulipes (or earwigs) have long mandibles/mouthparts and well-developed compound eyes. The antennae are long, filiform and with many segments. They are important natural enemies for FAW as their body structure can enable them to penetrate the hiding places of FAW such as the whorl or the ears. They are usually found in many numbers on a plant as they exhibit maternal care in the protection of hatched eggs and nymphs.

data.en: There are several different species of stem borers in Africa and Asia (Busseola fusca, Chilo partellus, Eldana saccharina, Sesamia inferens). The creamy white eggs are generally laid in a row under the leaf near the stem, and become dark after a few days. Caterpillars are black when they first hatch but then become light or dark violet, creamy or pinkish white, or yellowish brown. They have no hair and look shiny and smooth. Older caterpillars tunnel into the stem where they pupate.

data.en: FAW larvae can be affected and killed by a wide range of pathogens. Fungi (such as Beauveria, Metarhizium) infect FAW larvae through the body, and diseased larvae stop feeding, change colour (white, cream, green, reddish or brown) and eventually die as a hard cadaver. Bacteria (Bt) can infect and kill FAW. Viruses (SfGV, SfMNPV) cause the larvae to move to higher parts of the plant where it yellows with blemishes, stops feeding and dies while hanging its head down. The dead larvae are soft and dark in colour. Smashing them will cause further spread of the virus. Always look out for dead or infected larvae in the fields.
data.label: FAW larvae can be affected and killed by a wide range of pathogens. Fungi (such as Beauveria, Metarhizium) infect FAW larvae through the body, and diseased larvae stop feeding, change colour (white, cream, green, reddish or brown) and eventually die as a hard cadaver. Bacteria (Bt) can infect and kill FAW. Viruses (SfGV, SfMNPV) cause the larvae to move to higher parts of the plant where it yellows with blemishes, stops feeding and dies while hanging its head down. The dead larvae are soft and dark in colour. Smashing them will cause further spread of the virus. Always look out for dead or infected larvae in the fields.
